<span class="displaytext"><h3>switch shows caucus goers still deciding, indicates race is still wide open</h3><p>centerville, ia-- today governor (candidate full) welcomed susan klopfer as a new supporter to his campaign. </p><p>"we welcome susan and the tens of thousands of other supporters that have decided to stand with me on caucus night," (candidate last) said. "this just shows how fluid the race still is and the momentum my campaign is seeing on the ground. we are surging. we are confident we will surprise folks with a strong finish on jan. 3." </p><p>as nbc reports, klopfer had been volunteering for hilary (candidate last). she later switched her support to (candidate full). </p><p>but after hearing (candidate last) speak yesterday, klopfer again changed her position and decided to caucus for the new mexico governor on january 3. </p><p>"in both [(candidate last) and (candidate last)], i didn't see the experience that i'd like to see and kind of the groundedness that i'd like to see," klopfer told nbc. </p><p>klopfer added: "probably i'll caucus for (candidate last)." </p><p>"like susan, caucus goers across iowa are looking for real experience, proven results, and someone who can bring true change to washington," (candidate last) said. "there are a tremendous amount of undecided iowans still out there. and as they begin to decide who they will support on caucus night, i am confident they will see me as the most experienced candidate in the race and the one best ready to lead on day one."</p></span>



